headline: AI startup Modular raises $250 million, seeks to challenge Nvidia dominance
summary: (Reuters) -AI startup Modular said on Wednesday it raised $250 million in a funding round valuing it at $1.6 billion, as it aims to challenge Nvidia's software stranglehold on the AI computing market.  DFJ Growth and all existing investors, including GV, General Catalyst and Greylock also joined the round.  Founded in 2022 by veteran engineers at Apple and Google, Modular's platform is designed to allow developers to run their AI applications across a variety of computer chips without having to rewrite code for each one.

Founded in 2022 by veteran engineers at Apple and Google, Modular's platform is designed to allow developers to run their AI applications across a variety of computer chips without having to rewrite code for each one.

headline: Meta CEO Zuckerberg says Instagram has grown to 3 billion monthly active users
summary: Meta last disclosed Instagram's user figures in 2022 when Zuckerberg said the app had hit more than 2 billion monthly active users.  Meta, previously known as Facebook, bought Instagram for $1 billion in 2012, a move that had raised questions about the company's strategy as the social media app had begun with just photo-sharing without significant revenue.  Since then the app has grown astronomically and some firms have estimated it will make up more than half of Meta's U.S. ad revenue this year.

headline: Rattled by Trump's Chaotic H-1B Policy, US Firms Quietly Wait Out Changes
summary: The White House’s announcement Sept. 19 of a $100,000 fee sparked panic among employers and workers, particularly in the tech sector, which uses it to bring in trained engineers and programmers.  The initial frenzy has eased after officials clarified the fee wouldn’t apply to existing visa holders or renewals.  For businesses, one advantage of the wait-and-see approach is to avoid drawing the ire of the Trump administration, said Kathryn Wylde, chief executive officer of the Partnership for New York City.
